<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by WhiteFire on 01-17-2001 11:16 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Kal, 
  I looked at the Drawing you had and from what I saw it will not work.  Even if it did it would be very insucure.  What I would do in your position is setup up a Linux Firewall.  If you are not sure on how to setup one up I just posted a long message telling everything you would need and how to set it up.  You can read this post at <A HREF="http://www.ethernalquest.org/ubb/Forum3/HTML/001160.html" TARGET=_blank>http://www.ethernalquest.org/ubb/Forum3/HTML/001160.html</A>   

Now if you do not want to setup the Linux Firewall the other option is do somthing simular to what you had drawn.  The problem with your drawing is that you had shown the connection to your ISP going into a switch and then the switch plugged into a hub.  If you are going to det your computers up this way you only need one or the other a hub or a switch.  I would recomend using a hub seeing how switches route packets to the correct port and do not broadcast them to every host on the network.  The other suggestion I would make to you is depending on the brand of cablem modem you have you might need a Crossover cable going from the Cable modem to the hub.  Reason being is when the cable modem are installed the cable company only installs them for ONE PC not a network, so the manufactor of the Modem has a built in Crossover in the modem so you can plug in directly into the NIC card on the back of the computer with a regular patch cable.  Now if you want to plug the cable modem into a hug you might have to use a Crossover cable to reverse the crossover built into the modem.  The only other option is if your hub has a Uplink port you can plug the modem into that port and it has a crossover built into it that will do the same thing as the crossover cable.  

Now that everyone is confussed......Let me know if you have any questions.


Whitefire</TEXTAREA>
